[1] Germany
Date: Fri 20 May 2011
Source: Berliner Morgenpost [in German, trans. Corr.SB, abridged,
edited]
http://www.morgenpost.de/berlin/article1646236/In-Berlin-grassieren-wieder-die-Masern.html


Measles was considered to have been eradicated long ago. But the
number of cases is increasing again, and infection is widespread in
Berlin. Since the beginning of April 2011, 52 cases have been
diagnosed.

A general [campaign of] vaccination is not being undertaken. However,
the Robert Koch Institute strongly recommends implementation of an
enhanced vaccination program. This should include vaccinations against
whooping cough, measles, mumps, rubella, chickenpox and meningococcal
disease. Adults who have lived through these diseases in childhood
should have immunity against the most common bacterial and viral
diseases, but infants and young people require protection by
vaccination.

--
