[2] Spain
Date: Wed 18 May 2011
Source: Lne.es - Sociedad [in Spanish, trans. Corr.SB, abridged,
edited]
http://www.lne.es/sociedad-cultura/2011/05/18/salud-investiga-posible-brote-sarampion-area-caudal/1076407.html


The Health Department is investigating a possible outbreak of measles
in the Caudal area [Asturias, Spain]. A teenager was diagnosed
yesterday [17 May 2011], and today there will be an investigation to
see whether this is related to 2 others. None had been vaccinated.

The Caudal health area has now identified 4 cases in Asturias in
recent days. The last previous case of indigenous measles in the
principality dates back to 1999, and the last outbreak was in 1990.
The 4th case was found in the area of Gijon. This case is a foreign
citizen aged 41 years, and it is possible the disease was contracted
outside of Spain, but it may have been contracted in the capital of
the Costa Verde during Holy Week.

All 4 affected are out of danger. None of them had been vaccinated
against measles, because their parents did not approve of
vaccination.

The Head of the Public Health Agency says that the situation should
not cause alarm, since the protective efficacy of the vaccine is high,
and it is considered that the percentage of un-immunised people in
Asturias is very low. "However, the minority always creates risks,"
said Amelia Gonzalez.

By some estimates, the rate of vaccination against the disease in
Asturias is 99 percent, much higher coverage than the 82 percent in
Switzerland in the 1990s, the 90 percent in Britain between 1999 and
2006, or the 70 percent in Germany in infants born between 1996 and
2003.

Only one of 4 new cases of measles diagnosed these days is identified
by the Ministry of Health as "imported." The remaining 3 cases have
been labeled as "indigenous."

The last indigenous case was diagnosed in Asturias in 1999, and the
previous last outbreak in 1990 accounted for 1721 cases. However, a
case was detected in the principality in 2006: that of a girl from
Romania at a time when a major outbreak of the disease was occurring
in that country. In the principality, the latest death from infection
occurred in 1985.

Health authorities in the region note that "there are already many
pediatricians who have never seen a child with measles." This lack of
experience leads to a certain amount of "false positives," since to
some doctors, rash (red spots) signifies the presence of measles, but
the reality is different.

[Byline: Pablo Alvarez]

--
Communicated by:
HealthMap alerts via ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The principality of Asturias is an autonomous community within the
kingdom of Spain, the former Kingdom of Asturias in the Middle Ages.
It is situated on the Spanish north coast (Bay of Biscay) facing the
Cantabrian Sea, and can be located on the map at
http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Asturias. Caudal is one of 8
administrative divisions of Asturias. - Mod.CP]

