[4] UK (West Midlands)
Date: Thu 19 May 2011
Source: Coventry Telegraph [abridged & edited]
http://www.coventrytelegraph.net/news/coventry-news/2011/05/19/new-measles-cases-in-coventry-spark-vaccinations-plea-92746-28725153/


Parents are being urged to check that their children are up to date
with their vaccinations before travelling to Europe after a spate of
measles cases. In the last 2 months, there have been 3 confirmed cases
in Coventry and 9 in neighbouring Warwickshire. There are also a
further 22 suspected cases in the area.

This has prompted anyone taking children to Europe in the coming
weeks to check that they are fully immunised. Outbreaks of measles are
currently being reported in 24 European countries, including Belgium,
Denmark, France, Germany, Italy, the Netherlands, Romania, Russia,
Spain and Turkey.

Youngsters should have 2 doses of the MMR vaccine to protect them
from measles, mumps and rubella. Bronwen Spraggett, immunisation lead
for NHS Warwickshire, said: "With the levels of measles we are seeing
at the moment, there is no need to panic, but we are keen to ensure
that children and young people are protected from the disease."

