[6] Panama 1
Date: Wed 18 May 2011
Source: Prensa.com Panama [edited]
http://www.prensa.com/hoy/english/news_7184.asp


The Ministry of Health said on Tuesday [17 May 2011] that a teenager
has been diagnosed with the 1st case of measles to be reported in the
country in 16 years. Officials said the teenager recently arrived back
in Panama from a trip to Europe, where there have been outbreaks of
the disease.

Health official Itza Mosca said the teenager has been hospitalized
and that vaccines have been distributed to students at her school. "We
are taking all measures of control and prevention," Mosca said, adding
that vaccines have also been recommended for the teenager's relatives
and friends.

Panama's last case of measles was in 1995. "This is a case of measles
that was acquired outside the country, but the incubation period
started here," Mosca said. The health official said that anyone who
experiences a high fever and rashes on the face or body should go
immediately to the nearest clinic or hospital. The government provides
vaccines for measles free of charge.

