[7] Panama 2
Date: Fri 20 May 2011
Source: prensa.com [edited]
http://www.prensa.com/hoy/english/news_7194.asp


The Directorate of Epidemiology of the Ministry of Health announced
on Wednesday [18 May 2011] that it has detected 2 more cases of
measles. That brings the number of cases to 3, Panama's 1st outbreak
of the disease in 16 years. Those infected had all been on a trip to
Europe that recently concluded. The victims are all teenagers. The
teenagers arrived in Panama on 12 May 2011. Health official Itza de
Mosca said that 10 other cases are suspected.

Officials have started a mass vaccination of students attending the
schools which had students on the trip. Relatives of the students are
also being vaccinated.

The Pan-American Health Organization has recommended that people who
are going to leave the country be immunized at least 15 days before
leaving.

The last cases of measles were reported in Panama in 1995, when there
were 48 cases of the disease.

