[10] USA Update
Date: Sun 15 May 2011
Source: The Post Chronicle [abridged & edited]
http://www.postchronicle.com/news/original/article_212364156.shtml


The U.S. normally experiences only about 50 cases of measles in a
year, thanks to modern vaccines and health care improvements. But in
2011, nearly 100 cases have been reported thus far. Most outbreaks are
attributed to people traveling from other countries. According to a
recent AP [Associated Press] report, there have been several outbreaks
spanning the U.S. from east to west this year [2011].

In Florida, 5 cases were linked to an international helicopter trade
show held in Orlando last month [April 2011], and another 3 cases in
an outbreak in the Gainesville area were traced to a traveller who had
been to India.

9 cases in Utah reported last month [April 2011] were linked to
someone reportedly infected in Poland.

21 cases in Minnesota 1st reported in February 2011 were traced to a
Minneapolis-area child who developed symptoms after returning from a
trip to Kenya.

6 cases in Pennsylvania were 1st reported in January 2011 with origin
unknown.

The most recent state to report an outbreak is California, reporting
13 measles cases thus far, 7 reported in April 2011 alone; 4 patients
have been hospitalized, reports the L.A. Times.

[Byline: Jack Ryan]

