[14] USA (New York)
Date: Wed 18 May 2011
Source: Official Wire [abridged & edited]
http://www.officialwire.com/main.php?action=posted_news&rid=53181&catid=60


New York state health officials confirm a Rensselaer Polytechnic
Institute [RPI] student in Troy has measles and may have exposed the
public to the disease. Measles, a highly contagious disease, is spread
by contact with nasal or throat secretions -- like coughing or
sneezing -- of infected people. Germs can stay in the air for 2 hours,
the New York State Department of Health said.

State and local health departments are advising people who may have
been exposed and who have symptoms consistent with measles to call
their healthcare providers or a local emergency room before going for
care to help prevent others in a healthcare setting from being exposed
to the disease.

RPI officials say 10 students have not been immunized for measles,
including the student who currently has measles. Preventive treatment
for measles must be given within 6 days of the exposure to be
effective.

Measles exposure may have occurred at the RPI campus from 8-16 May
2011; a health food store and drug store on 12 May 2011; Troy's
Samaritan Hospital emergency room on 12-13 May 2011, and Albany
Medical Center Hospital emergency room on 13-24 May 2011.

