[15] USA (Utah)
Date: Tue 17 May 2011
Source: Salt Lake Valley Health Department [edited]
http://www.slvhealth.org/media/2011/pdf/20110517.pdf


The Salt Lake Valley Health Department (SLVHD) in Utah says the
recent measles outbreak has ended, with a total of 9 confirmed cases
that cost approximately USD 130 000. Health officials say the county's
more than 97 percent measles vaccination rate for students in grades
K-12 helped curtail the spread of the disease, but they point out that
17 300 students, along with infants and individuals with compromised
immune systems, remain unvaccinated. The department says 7 confirmed
cases were tied to 2 schools where 22.7 percent of unvaccinated
students became sick, compared to 0.1 percent of vaccinated students.
SLVHD medical officer Dr. Dagmar Vitek emphasizes the importance of
both children and adults ensuring that their vaccination status is
up-to-date, especially as measles and other vaccine-preventable
diseases continue to circulate. He says vaccination enables
individuals to protect themselves as well as those who cannot be
vaccinated.

